    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1786648316" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1786648316" />
    <a title="Ben Thurley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7459837-ben-thurley"><img alt="Ben Thurley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349591390p2/7459837.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1786648316?book_show_action=true">Oct 17, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben Thurley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben Thurley" href="/user/show/7459837-ben-thurley">Ben Thurley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780571231218" href="/book/show/1220212.Sacred_Games">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7459837-ben-thurley?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1786648316" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11954949869115769151">Glorious. Almost unutterably wonderful.<br/><br/>It is simply sublime how Vikram Chandra makes poetry and spine-tingling human drama from what – on the face of it – should be an overstuffed airport-novel blend of police procedural, espionage thriller, love story and gangster tale. <i>Sacred Games</i> is rich, ribald, cunning, sharply plotted (for all its sprawling 900 pages) and it mainlines deep into your brain through sentences of sensuous beauty.<br/><br/>From the first sentence of the first chapter, &quot;Policeman&apos;s Day&quot;,</span>
  <span id="freeText11954949869115769151" style="display:none">Glorious. Almost unutterably wonderful.<br /><br />It is simply sublime how Vikram Chandra makes poetry and spine-tingling human drama from what – on the face of it – should be an overstuffed airport-novel blend of police procedural, espionage thriller, love story and gangster tale. <i>Sacred Games</i> is rich, ribald, cunning, sharply plotted (for all its sprawling 900 pages) and it mainlines deep into your brain through sentences of sensuous beauty.<br /><br />From the first sentence of the first chapter, "Policeman's Day", you know you are in for something special. <blockquote>A white Pomeranian named Fluffy flew out of a fifth-floor window, in Panna, which was a brand-new building with the painter's scaffolding still around it. Fluffy screamed in her little lap-dog voice all the way down, like a little white kettle losing steam, bounced off the bonnet of a Cielo, and skidded to a halt near the rank of schoolgirls waiting for the St Mary's Convent bus.</blockquote>It's a stunningly effective introduction to the living, sprawling, setting of Mumbai, some of the novel's strongest themes: love and degradation, cruelty and indifference, and to one of the main characters, the dapper, more-than-slightly-jaded, and almost-honest-almost-humane police inspector, Sartaj Singh.<br /><br />By the end of the first chapter, we have also been introduced to Ganesh Gaitonde, feared crime boss, holed up in a concrete bunker beneath the city. Afraid, it seems, to come to the surface. <br /><br />The novel is told in fragmented and interlocking chapters and points of view. One main thread tells the story of Sartaj's investigations, as he manoeuvres through the thicket of police and national politics, and through violence and tragedy, and a rising dread of what he'll find on the other side of his investigation into Gaitonde. The other thread works forwards from Ganesh Gaitonde's past to recount his rise from brutalised streetfighting youth to international crimelord and wannabe film producer. There's both a brutal fascination and a deeply humanising power in Chandra's writing that compelled me to love even the deeply unloveable, hideously violent, relentlessly energetic, barely self-aware, Gaitonde. <blockquote>I was walking under the whirling sky riven by clouds, with the unceasing tug of gold on my back and the city ahead. I was nineteen and I had gold on my back. Here I was, Ganesh Gaitonde, wearing a dirty blue shirt, brown pants, torn rubber-bottomed shoes and no socks, with forty-seven rupees in my pocket and a revolver in my belt and gold on my back.</blockquote><br /><br />There are also a series "insets" which at first appear self-contained and even tangential to the main story but (particularly the closing two) are as beautifully realised short stories as any I've read. And not only do they give depth to some of the incidents in the main story arc, but they draw out personal and political contexts of post-colonial India and Pakistan in immensely powerful ways.<br /><br />Ultimately, though, the novel is a triumph because – as with Sartaj and Gaitonde – Chandra creates characters you love and live with. Sartaj and Gaitonde of course. But so many more that it's almost possible to lose track. Sartaj's partner, Katekar, and Gaitonde's madam, Jojo. The dog-defenestrating Pandeys. And so many more.<br /><br />Chandra builds up character painstakingly but seemingly without effort, through moments of human connection, submerged gender battles and raging street fights, jags of hope and fear, slow drifts of ageing and dying, short sharp shocks and slowly dawning realisations of another person's reality and the way it intersects with your own. A small example that struck me, from many I could have chosen, when his mother jokes that she, too, is a police-walli, Sartaj reflects: <blockquote>It was strange to think of love as duty, to imagine that Ma's salwar-kameez and red paranda had been a kind of uniform, that maybe her assiduous care of his and Papa-ji's health and cleanliness and nutrition had not been natural, but somehow cultivated and consciously sacrificed. So this familiar figure resting next to him had led her own private life in all the homes they had shared, she had her own history of every birthday, every journey. Again Sartaj had that unsettling feeling that this woman, his own mother, Prabhjot Kaur, was also someone he did not know. It wrenched his heart, just slightly, but out of that hurt came a new affection for this stranger he had lived with all these years.</blockquote><br /><br />What can I say? It's gripping. It's beautiful. It's filthy. (I don't speak Hindi, but am pretty sure that I've learned some really dirty Hindi words thanks to both the criminals and police in the novel.) This is a novel I'll read and re-read.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11954949869115769151" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


