  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_88199155" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/88199155" />
    <a title="Robyn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/173077-robyn"><img alt="Robyn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1441760919p2/173077.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/88199155?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robyn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robyn" href="/user/show/173077-robyn">Robyn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer88199155" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17129886879742719402">I was looking for an Indian detective novel, and I surely found it. You have to commit yourself to this book, because it&apos;s an Indian novel in the Mahabbarata style...900 pages long. But if you do commit, there are several rewards. One, you&apos;ll learn all the Hindi/Urdu curse words you&apos;ll ever need to know, and find yourself wanting to randomly sprinkle them into conversation. Two, you&apos;ll find yourself addressing your cats as &quot;Kevin-ji&quot; and &quot;Gilly saab,&quot; which is kind of cool, though puzzling to th</span>
  <span id="freeText17129886879742719402" style="display:none">I was looking for an Indian detective novel, and I surely found it. You have to commit yourself to this book, because it's an Indian novel in the Mahabbarata style...900 pages long. But if you do commit, there are several rewards. One, you'll learn all the Hindi/Urdu curse words you'll ever need to know, and find yourself wanting to randomly sprinkle them into conversation. Two, you'll find yourself addressing your cats as "Kevin-ji" and "Gilly saab," which is kind of cool, though puzzling to the cats. Three, you'll develop a deep, bodily craving for Indian food. Four, you'll have the opportunity to get as close as possible to living in modern-day Mumbai/Bombay for as long as it takes you to finish the novel, without picking up any unpleasant parasites along the way. Five, as with any of the really good long, long Indian novels (like A Suitable Boy), you'll find yourself missing the characters for several days after you've finished. In Ganesh Gaitonde you get a kind of Indian version of Tony Soprano, only it's a novel, so you get first person accounts of his life and why he is the way he is. In Sartaj Singh, you get the Indian (specifically, Skikh) version of the classic noir detective...not really good and not really bad either. Six, and probably one of my most important criteria for a good book, you might find yourself wondering about what it all meant, perhaps for as long as it took you to read the thing in the first place.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17129886879742719402" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

